00:01:53.160 --> 00:01:56.960
Daniel K. Inouye was a
lionesque figure in Washington

00:01:56.960 --> 00:01:59.750
and in his home state of Hawaii.

00:01:59.750 --> 00:02:05.050
Born September 7th, 1924 in
Honolulu, Inouye graduated

00:02:05.050 --> 00:02:07.070
from high school not six months

00:02:07.070 --> 00:02:11.800
after the United States
entered into war against Japan.

00:02:11.800 --> 00:02:15.470
Coming out of the University
of Hawaii as a premed student,

00:02:15.470 --> 00:02:18.400
Inouye volunteered and
was the youngest member

00:02:18.400 --> 00:02:22.500
of the famous 442nd
regiment of the US Army --

00:02:22.500 --> 00:02:26.980
a unit of Japanese-American
soldiers who fought gallantly

00:02:26.980 --> 00:02:30.630
in the European theatre
of operations.

00:02:30.630 --> 00:02:34.890
On April 21st, 1945
Inouye was wounded

00:02:34.890 --> 00:02:38.780
in battle and lost his right arm.

00:02:38.780 --> 00:02:42.620
He returned home with a
Distinguished Service Cross,

00:02:42.620 --> 00:02:45.550
Bronze Star Medal,
two Purple Hearts,

00:02:45.550 --> 00:02:48.910
and 12 other medals and citations.

00:02:48.910 --> 00:02:53.330
From there Inouye graduated
college and law school

00:02:53.330 --> 00:02:56.230
and entered into public service.

00:02:56.230 --> 00:02:59.380
Elected into the territorial
House of Representatives

00:02:59.380 --> 00:03:03.500
when Hawaii became the
nation's 50th state,

00:03:03.500 --> 00:03:07.220
Inouye became Hawaii's first
representative to the US House,

00:03:07.220 --> 00:03:09.840
followed by his election
to the US Senate

00:03:09.840 --> 00:03:14.360
as America's first
Japanese-American senator.

00:03:14.360 --> 00:03:18.930 position:56%
In his near half a century in
Washington Inouye served as a member

00:03:18.930 --> 00:03:20.860
of the Senate Watergate Committee,

00:03:20.860 --> 00:03:25.040
chairman of the Senate Iran-Contra
Committee, and long-time member

00:03:25.040 --> 00:03:27.320
of the Senate Appropriations
Committee,

00:03:27.320 --> 00:03:32.500
which he chaired from 2009 to 2012.

00:03:32.500 --> 00:03:37.810
Inouye passed away on
December 17th, 2012.

00:03:37.810 --> 00:03:40.830
He was awarded the
Congressional Medal of Honor

00:03:40.830 --> 00:03:42.810
for his military service

00:03:42.810 --> 00:03:47.080
and was posthumously awarded the
Presidential Medal of Freedom,

00:03:47.080 --> 00:03:50.930
becoming the first senator
to receive both the Medal

00:03:50.930 --> 00:03:53.840
of Freedom and the Medal of Honor.

00:03:53.840 --> 00:03:57.810
Tonight the John W. Kluge Center
at the Library of Congress

00:03:57.810 --> 00:04:01.550
and the Daniel K. Inouye
