00:13:07.650 --> 00:13:11.220
And Secretary Mineta,
let's start with you.

00:13:11.220 --> 00:13:16.000
Tell us about moving into that
internment camp and tell us

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:20.300
about the cane that you carry now.

00:13:20.300 --> 00:13:23.230
&gt;&gt; Norman Mineta: Well, seminal --

00:13:23.230 --> 00:13:25.310
because I'm going to
personalize this --

00:13:25.310 --> 00:13:32.330 position:56%
but probably the most seminal moment
in my life was December 7th, 1941.

00:13:32.330 --> 00:13:37.400
We had just returned home from
church and we had the radio on.

00:13:37.400 --> 00:13:41.950
And pretty soon people were calling
about "What's going on in Hawaii,

00:13:41.950 --> 00:13:47.200
and how is that going to
impact on us on the mainland?"

00:13:47.200 --> 00:13:53.110
And so in February 19th

00:13:53.110 --> 00:13:59.090
of 1942 President Roosevelt
signed Executive Order 9066.

00:13:59.090 --> 00:14:04.220
And that order delegated
to the Secretary of the War

00:14:04.220 --> 00:14:05.600
and to the Commanding General

00:14:05.600 --> 00:14:11.120 position:56%
of the Western Civil Defense Command
the ability to evacuate persons.

00:14:11.120 --> 00:14:16.870
It didn't say German, Japanese,
Italian; it said just the ability

00:14:16.870 --> 00:14:20.710
to evacuate and intern persons.

00:14:20.710 --> 00:14:22.010
The Commanding General

00:14:22.010 --> 00:14:26.870
of the Western Civil Defense
Command was a General Dewitt.

00:14:26.870 --> 00:14:31.030
And General Dewitt postured
that if the Japanese were able

00:14:31.030 --> 00:14:34.330
to attack Hawaii, they
would probably be able

00:14:34.330 --> 00:14:36.840
to attack the West Coast.

00:14:36.840 --> 00:14:41.090
And then if they attacked
the West Coast,

00:14:41.090 --> 00:14:46.210
because there were 120,000 people
of Japanese ancestry in Washington,

00:14:46.210 --> 00:14:50.450
Oregon, and California,
he had coined the phrase

00:14:50.450 --> 00:14:53.720
"Once a J-a-p, always a J-a-p."

00:14:53.720 --> 00:14:57.460
And if he figured if the
military forces came,

00:14:57.460 --> 00:15:02.380
120,000 people would join
up with the military forces.

00:15:02.380 --> 00:15:10.560
So he used Executive Order
9066 to commandeer racetracks

00:15:10.560 --> 00:15:16.090
and county fairgrounds because
they had built-in living quarters,

00:15:16.090 --> 00:15:18.060
namely horse stables.

00:15:18.060 --> 00:15:23.180
And so soon after February
19th, the big placards went

00:15:23.180 --> 00:15:24.970
up in those neighborhoods

00:15:24.970 --> 00:15:30.920
where there were many
people of Japanese ancestry.

00:15:30.920 --> 00:15:34.210
And the big signs just said simply

00:15:34.210 --> 00:15:40.300
"Attention all those Japanese
ancestry, alien and nonalien."

00:15:40.300 --> 00:15:43.190
And even as ten-year-old
kid as I was reading

00:15:43.190 --> 00:15:46.410
that I said, "What's a nonalien?"

00:15:46.410 --> 00:15:50.250
I asked my brother, who was 19
-- nine years old than me --

00:15:50.250 --> 00:15:52.720
he said, "That's you, a citizen."

00:15:52.720 --> 00:15:56.060
I said, "Well, why isn't the
government calling me a citizen

00:15:56.060 --> 00:15:59.520
instead of a nonalien?"

00:15:59.520 --> 00:16:03.720
Now, I'm not sure how many
of you have ever stood up

00:16:03.720 --> 00:16:07.470
and pounded your chest and
said, "I'm a proud nonalien

00:16:07.470 --> 00:16:09.910
of the United States of America"?

00:16:09.910 --> 00:16:11.560
I don't think you have.

00:16:11.560 --> 00:16:16.550
And that's why to this day
I cherish the word "citizen"

00:16:16.550 --> 00:16:23.580
because my own government wasn't
willing to use that moniker on us.

00:16:23.580 --> 00:16:33.050
So by May of 1942, we were
being assembled to move

00:16:33.050 --> 00:16:36.460
onto the internment sites.

00:16:36.460 --> 00:16:39.790
And we could only take
what we could carry.

00:16:39.790 --> 00:16:46.380
And so we were first put into
-- imprisoned at Santa Anita,

00:16:46.380 --> 00:16:50.950
the racetrack, which is
400 miles from San Jose.

00:16:50.950 --> 00:16:57.180 position:56%
So for us it was a big, long
overnight train ride to Los Angeles,

00:16:57.180 --> 00:16:59.400
to Santa Anita, the racetrack.

00:16:59.400 --> 00:17:06.530
And I was ten years old and had
my Cub Scout uniform on, baseball,

00:17:06.530 --> 00:17:09.470
baseball glove, baseball bat.

00:17:09.470 --> 00:17:14.040
And as I got on the train,
the MP's confiscated my bat

00:17:14.040 --> 00:17:17.560
on the basis it could be
used as a lethal weapon.

00:17:17.560 --> 00:17:19.960
So I went running to my father,

00:17:19.960 --> 00:17:23.080
crying that the MP's
had taken the bat.

00:17:23.080 --> 00:17:24.780
He said, "That's all right.

00:17:24.780 --> 00:17:26.550
We'll get it replaced."

00:17:26.550 --> 00:17:31.890
But there were no stores in the
camps, so it never was replaced.

00:17:31.890 --> 00:17:35.260
So I did lose my bat at the time.

00:17:35.260 --> 00:17:43.690
And 1991 I wrote the Intermodal
Surface Transportation Efficiency

00:17:43.690 --> 00:17:46.870
Act and that was considered
landmark legislation.

00:17:46.870 --> 00:17:50.990
It was the first rewrite of the
National Defense Highway Act.

00:17:50.990 --> 00:17:57.110
And the American Society of
Civil Engineers gave me the honor

00:17:57.110 --> 00:18:04.010
of being a fellow of the American
Society of Civil Engineers.

00:18:04.010 --> 00:18:06.810
A fellow wrote to me
from Los Angeles saying,

00:18:06.810 --> 00:18:09.190 position:56%
"Congratulations on becoming fellow.

00:18:09.190 --> 00:18:12.300
And I was very touched by the
fact that you lost your bat

00:18:12.300 --> 00:18:13.930
when you were ten years old.

00:18:13.930 --> 00:18:17.920
And I want to share with you
a bat from my collection."

00:18:17.920 --> 00:18:22.000
And when I opened the box it was
a bat signed by Hank Aaron --

00:18:22.000 --> 00:18:28.200 position:56%
he was home run king -- and Sadaharu
Oh, the home run king of Japan.

00:18:28.200 --> 00:18:30.800
And so I thought wow.

00:18:30.800 --> 00:18:32.100
And so --

00:18:32.100 --> 00:18:34.960
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: But that's
not the end of the story.

00:18:34.960 --> 00:18:38.590
&gt;&gt; Norman Mineta: So I wrote the
fellow a letter profusely thanking

00:18:38.590 --> 00:18:41.320
him for this wonderful gift.

00:18:41.320 --> 00:18:43.980
And a reporter from the <i>San
Jose Mercury News</i> heard

00:18:43.980 --> 00:18:48.160
about my getting the bat, so
he wrote a story about the bat.

00:18:48.160 --> 00:18:51.770
Being an enterprising reporter
went to -- excuse me --

00:18:51.770 --> 00:18:57.560
a sports memorabilia shop, found
out the bat was worth $1,500.

00:18:57.560 --> 00:19:03.390
Well, the gift limitation for
those of us in Congress was $250.

00:19:03.390 --> 00:19:07.480
So I had to pack up the bat, send
it back to him, and explaining

00:19:07.480 --> 00:19:11.090
to him why I couldn't
accept the bat.

00:19:11.090 --> 00:19:14.520
And I sent a copy of that
letter to the reporter.

00:19:14.520 --> 00:19:19.510
I penned on there, "The damn
government's taken my bat again."

00:19:19.510 --> 00:19:22.240
[ Laughter ]

00:19:22.240 --> 00:19:24.910
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: Mr. Secretary,
I'm going to bring Alan Simpson

00:19:24.910 --> 00:19:29.820
into this now because what was
it like for you as a kid growing

00:19:29.820 --> 00:19:35.140
up in Cody, Wyoming to go out
and visit families during wartime

00:19:35.140 --> 00:19:39.050 position:56%
who were basically American citizens
prisoner in their own country?

00:19:39.050 --> 00:19:43.540 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Alan Simpson: Well, it was a very
confounding time because the war --

00:19:43.540 --> 00:19:48.710
December 7th, a beautiful
Sunday, suddenly they said,

00:19:48.710 --> 00:19:51.580
"The Japs have attacked
Pearl Harbor."

00:19:51.580 --> 00:19:55.650
There was no political
correctness in those days.

00:19:55.650 --> 00:19:59.110
One of the cartoons in
the interpretive center,

00:19:59.110 --> 00:20:05.150
a very racist cartoon of the
first order by Dr. Seuss.

00:20:05.150 --> 00:20:07.790
Most amazing thing to
look at, the guy that went

00:20:07.790 --> 00:20:09.650
on to charm the millions.

00:20:09.650 --> 00:20:12.460
It was a time of hysteria.

00:20:12.460 --> 00:20:15.070
But what it was really
time, there was nothing

00:20:15.070 --> 00:20:18.190
between Powell and
Cody but sagebrush.

00:20:18.190 --> 00:20:24.090
And suddenly in the
June, May of '42 --

00:20:24.090 --> 00:20:28.080
don't forget a Japanese
submarine shelled the coast

00:20:28.080 --> 00:20:32.170
of California in March of '42.

00:20:32.170 --> 00:20:37.470
And they said, "How could this
possibly have happened unless

00:20:37.470 --> 00:20:39.980
they're spies?"

00:20:39.980 --> 00:20:44.530
So they didn't gather up anybody in
Cedar Rapids or Denver or New York.

00:20:44.530 --> 00:20:48.420
They just took them right
off the coast -- 120,000 --

00:20:48.420 --> 00:20:54.200
and 14,000 people came to the
sagebrush between Cody and Powell;

00:20:54.200 --> 00:20:59.170
about fifteen miles from
Cody, ten from Powell.

00:20:59.170 --> 00:21:05.390
And it had barbed wire,
the entire enclosure.

00:21:05.390 --> 00:21:06.690
It was barracks.

00:21:06.690 --> 00:21:09.490
As far as you could see, barracks.

00:21:09.490 --> 00:21:13.950 position:56%
No toilets in any of the facilities,
just a mess house where they ate,

00:21:13.950 --> 00:21:18.650
and then their toilet in a
tar paper shack -- literally.

00:21:18.650 --> 00:21:21.560
And they got off the train.

00:21:21.560 --> 00:21:26.560
And at each corner were
guard towers with soldiers

00:21:26.560 --> 00:21:30.290
and machine guns aimed inside.

00:21:30.290 --> 00:21:34.400
Now, when you're a kid and you're
hearing on the radio every day

00:21:34.400 --> 00:21:41.420
that the Japs have killed people
in Iwo Jima and they were taking us

00:21:41.420 --> 00:21:47.580
to the woodshed until Midway
Island came up and we blew

00:21:47.580 --> 00:21:48.880
up a lot of their carriers.

00:21:48.880 --> 00:21:50.800
But it was a tough time.

00:21:50.800 --> 00:21:56.710
Signs on the door in Cody, Wyoming,
"No Japs allowed," or "You SOB,

00:21:56.710 --> 00:21:59.400
you killed my son in Iwo Jima."

00:21:59.400 --> 00:22:03.040
And our scout master --
very advanced fellow --

00:22:03.040 --> 00:22:05.980
said, "Look, they've got
scout troops out there."

00:22:05.980 --> 00:22:10.410
I think there were three troops
and one was from San Jose.

00:22:10.410 --> 00:22:15.610 position:56%
And he said, "If any of your parents
don't want you to go, you tell me."

00:22:15.610 --> 00:22:19.710
And only one parent said no.

00:22:19.710 --> 00:22:23.160
And my parents said,
"These are kids.

00:22:23.160 --> 00:22:25.150
They're just like you."

00:22:25.150 --> 00:22:30.670
And we went out there and just
did merit badges and braiding.

00:22:30.670 --> 00:22:34.800
I didn't have any hair to braid,
but we braided other things.

00:22:34.800 --> 00:22:36.100
And met this cat.

00:22:36.100 --> 00:22:38.780
And then it never ended.

00:22:38.780 --> 00:22:43.410
He said that I tried to
drown out a bully in his camp

00:22:43.410 --> 00:22:45.320
and that I made this
hideous laughter.

00:22:45.320 --> 00:22:47.010
I know that's not true.

00:22:47.010 --> 00:22:48.470
[ Laughter ]

00:22:48.470 --> 00:22:55.250
But nevertheless, it was
a great lesson in working

00:22:55.250 --> 00:23:00.620
through the confusion of a terrible
situation and seeing boys just --

00:23:00.620 --> 00:23:05.460
same merit badges, same
little books, same stuff.

00:23:05.460 --> 00:23:06.760
Terrible.

00:23:06.760 --> 00:23:11.500
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: So here we are
in 2016 and we've been through --

00:23:11.500 --> 00:23:18.290
both of you -- have been
through 2001 and September 11th.

00:23:18.290 --> 00:23:23.290 position:56%
Are there lessons from the
internment process at a time of war,

00:23:23.290 --> 00:23:27.810
after a time of real attack by a
known country, a known adversary

00:23:27.810 --> 00:23:32.870
to a time now where this shadowy
terrorism and the rise of ISIS?

00:23:32.870 --> 00:23:36.290
What lessons do you take from this?

00:23:36.290 --> 00:23:39.940
And in the rear view mirror, does
the internment seem terribly,

00:23:39.940 --> 00:23:43.660
terribly wrong or understandable
at the time?

00:23:43.660 --> 00:23:45.480
Senator?

00:23:45.480 --> 00:23:48.840
&gt;&gt; Alan Simpson: Well,
there's a difference.

00:23:48.840 --> 00:23:57.890
The difference is after we rounded
up 120,000 Japanese-Americans,

00:23:57.890 --> 00:24:00.820
very few of them were
permanent resident aliens --

00:24:00.820 --> 00:24:05.360
some were -- the Nisei
and the Issei.

00:24:05.360 --> 00:24:13.770
There wasn't one single case of
espionage by any Japanese-American

00:24:13.770 --> 00:24:15.940
in any one of those camps.

00:24:15.940 --> 00:24:20.330
It's different this time because
you're dealing with apparently

00:24:20.330 --> 00:24:23.560
and vividly -- and
don't throw anything --

00:24:23.560 --> 00:24:29.580
of people who like to behead people
and give women contraceptives

00:24:29.580 --> 00:24:32.770
because you're not supposed to ever
rape a woman who could be pregnant.

00:24:32.770 --> 00:24:34.260
These are not pleasant people.

00:24:34.260 --> 00:24:39.600
And at some point you have to
make a distinction without getting

00:24:39.600 --> 00:24:45.120
into hysteria and racism that
it's a very different thing now.

00:24:45.120 --> 00:24:47.240
And that's not very
politically correct.

00:24:47.240 --> 00:24:50.400
And you're going to have
to deal with real refugees.

00:24:50.400 --> 00:24:56.180
And a real refugee is a person
fleeing persecution based on race,

00:24:56.180 --> 00:24:58.060
religion, national origin,

00:24:58.060 --> 00:25:01.300
or membership in a political
or social organization.

00:25:01.300 --> 00:25:05.770
The dogs are tracking you
and the gunners are aiming

00:25:05.770 --> 00:25:08.050
at you -- that's a refugee.

00:25:08.050 --> 00:25:10.880
And if that definition
isn't met case by case --

00:25:10.880 --> 00:25:13.520
which was something
that Kennedy and I did

00:25:13.520 --> 00:25:16.890
and George Shultz --
you got real problems.

00:25:16.890 --> 00:25:19.360
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: Mr.
Secretary, looking back,

00:25:19.360 --> 00:25:24.180
what should those students who are
listening to us from Hawaii know

00:25:24.180 --> 00:25:29.430
about how you look at the
internment and how you look

00:25:29.430 --> 00:25:30.800
at the security threat now?

00:25:30.800 --> 00:25:36.570 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Norman Mineta: Well, I was the
Secretary of Transportation on 9/11.

00:25:36.570 --> 00:25:40.640 position:56%
And I was having a breakfast meeting
with the Deputy Prime Minister

00:25:40.640 --> 00:25:46.610
of Belgium, who's also the
Minister of Transport for Belgium.

00:25:46.610 --> 00:25:49.490
And I had with me Jane
Garvey, who was the head

00:25:49.490 --> 00:25:52.260
of the Federal Aviation
Administration.

00:25:52.260 --> 00:25:57.600
The three of us were having
breakfast in my conference room.

00:25:57.600 --> 00:26:00.570
My chief of staff came in
and said, "May I see you?"

00:26:00.570 --> 00:26:03.410
So I excused myself,
went into my office.

00:26:03.410 --> 00:26:05.090
As I went into my office,

00:26:05.090 --> 00:26:09.080
at the other end is a
TV console on the floor.

00:26:09.080 --> 00:26:13.270
And as I come walking in, obviously
it's the World Trade Center

00:26:13.270 --> 00:26:15.540
and black smoke pouring out.

00:26:15.540 --> 00:26:16.840
I said, "What's all this?"

00:26:16.840 --> 00:26:18.140
They said, "Well, we don't know.

00:26:18.140 --> 00:26:21.070
We've heard general
aviation into the building,

00:26:21.070 --> 00:26:23.920
we've heard the possibility
of a commercial airliner

00:26:23.920 --> 00:26:26.030
into the building, we've
heard the possibility

00:26:26.030 --> 00:26:29.120
of an internal explosion
in the building."

00:26:29.120 --> 00:26:34.390
So I looked at the TV for a
little while and went back

00:26:34.390 --> 00:26:36.830
into the conference room
and explained to Jane

00:26:36.830 --> 00:26:41.350
and to Mrs. [inaudible]
what I had just seen.

00:26:41.350 --> 00:26:48.060
And so little later he came back
in and said, "May I see you?"

00:26:48.060 --> 00:26:50.990
So I excused myself,
went into my office,

00:26:50.990 --> 00:26:54.340
and he said it was a
commercial airliner

00:26:54.340 --> 00:26:55.640
that went into the building.

00:26:55.640 --> 00:26:58.870
And I was standing in
front of the TV set.

00:26:58.870 --> 00:27:01.970
And then all of a sudden
I see something green go

00:27:01.970 --> 00:27:05.900
across the screen, disappear on
the left-hand side of the screen,

00:27:05.900 --> 00:27:09.400
this yellow orangey billowy cloud.

00:27:09.400 --> 00:27:11.960
And I said, "Holy cow.

00:27:11.960 --> 00:27:14.410
What was all that about?"

00:27:14.410 --> 00:27:18.870
or words to that effect.

00:27:18.870 --> 00:27:22.190
So I really watched
TV for a little while.

00:27:22.190 --> 00:27:25.600 position:56%
And I finally went into the room and
I said, "I don't know what's going

00:27:25.600 --> 00:27:28.940
on in New York, but I know
it's going to involve me.

00:27:28.940 --> 00:27:31.940
Jane, you've got to get back to
the operation center at the FAA

00:27:31.940 --> 00:27:35.700
and we've got to deal
with whatever's going on."

00:27:35.700 --> 00:27:38.800
So I excused myself and
went back into my office.

00:27:38.800 --> 00:27:41.770
By the time I got in there,
the White House called, said,

00:27:41.770 --> 00:27:43.490
"Get over here right away."

00:27:43.490 --> 00:27:45.520
So I went over to the White House.

00:27:45.520 --> 00:27:49.270
And as we're driving in, people
are running out of the White House,

00:27:49.270 --> 00:27:52.760
they're running out of the
old executive office building.

00:27:52.760 --> 00:27:54.650
And I said to my driver
and security guy,

00:27:54.650 --> 00:27:57.320
"Is there something
wrong with this picture?

00:27:57.320 --> 00:28:00.980
We're driving in and
everybody else is running out."

00:28:00.980 --> 00:28:05.510
So I went into the White
House and Dick Clarke said,

00:28:05.510 --> 00:28:06.810
"You got to be [inaudible].

00:28:06.810 --> 00:28:10.090
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: He was the
counterterrorism advisor

00:28:10.090 --> 00:28:11.390
at the time.

00:28:11.390 --> 00:28:12.690
&gt;&gt; Norman Mineta: "You
have to be briefed

00:28:12.690 --> 00:28:13.990
in the situation room
by Dick Clarke."

00:28:13.990 --> 00:28:16.160
So I went in there and he
didn't really tell me much more

00:28:16.160 --> 00:28:19.240
than what I had already
heard on television.

00:28:19.240 --> 00:28:21.590
Then he said, "You got
to be in the PEOC."

00:28:21.590 --> 00:28:24.450
And I said, "The PEOC,
what is that?"

00:28:24.450 --> 00:28:28.930
He said, "That's the Presidential
Emergency Operation Center.

00:28:28.930 --> 00:28:31.320
It's a bunker way under
the White House."

00:28:31.320 --> 00:28:33.440
I said, "I have no
idea where it is."

00:28:33.440 --> 00:28:37.010
Secret Service agent standing
there said, "I'll take you."

00:28:37.010 --> 00:28:40.520
So I went over there and
got there probably about --

00:28:40.520 --> 00:28:45.040
I think it was about 9:20 or so.

00:28:45.040 --> 00:28:48.040 position:56%
And the vice-president was in there.

00:28:48.040 --> 00:28:54.710
And so military aid came in,
said to the vice-president,

00:28:54.710 --> 00:28:58.100
"There's a plane heading
towards DC."

00:28:58.100 --> 00:29:05.150
So in the POEC there's a big, long
table probably 30 feet long; 12,

00:29:05.150 --> 00:29:08.190
15 feet wide; chairs
all the way around;

00:29:08.190 --> 00:29:10.990
phones between each of the chairs.

00:29:10.990 --> 00:29:15.220
This phone I set up to my
office, this one to FAA,

00:29:15.220 --> 00:29:21.470
sat there at that desk
talking into both phones.

00:29:21.470 --> 00:29:26.670
And so when he said that there
was a plane coming towards DC,

00:29:26.670 --> 00:29:30.100
said to the FAA people,
"What are you tracking

00:29:30.100 --> 00:29:33.190
of a plane coming towards DC?"

00:29:33.190 --> 00:29:38.130
And in the credenza behind my desk
I had a monitor with an outline

00:29:38.130 --> 00:29:41.600
of the 48 states and
a whole bunch of dots.

00:29:41.600 --> 00:29:45.660
I put my mouse on one of those
dots and a flag would come up

00:29:45.660 --> 00:29:53.250
and say UA 123 -- United
Airlines flight 123 --

00:29:53.250 --> 00:29:57.200
PDX and then a number of
navigational points, ORD.

00:29:57.200 --> 00:29:59.330
So the plane had left Portland,

00:29:59.330 --> 00:30:03.010
flying through these points,
going to Chicago O'Hare.

00:30:03.010 --> 00:30:11.640
And then it would say D757 52
-- a Boeing 757 Series 200.

00:30:11.640 --> 00:30:16.240
It would show the compass
direction, the amount of fuel left

00:30:16.240 --> 00:30:18.870
on the plane, and a
number of other things.

00:30:18.870 --> 00:30:22.840
But all that transponder had
been turned off on that plane.

00:30:22.840 --> 00:30:25.360
And all they were doing
was following the blip

00:30:25.360 --> 00:30:30.270 position:56%
on the 37-second sweep of the radar.

00:30:30.270 --> 00:30:33.730
So I said [inaudible]
"Where's the plane?"

00:30:33.730 --> 00:30:38.460
And it's hard to relate to
a radar picture and then try

00:30:38.460 --> 00:30:40.610
to relate it to the ground.

00:30:40.610 --> 00:30:43.920
So he said, "Well, probably in
the middle of Pennsylvania."

00:30:43.920 --> 00:30:46.280
So every so often I'd
say, "Where is it now?"

00:30:46.280 --> 00:30:48.220
And so he'd try to guess.

00:30:48.220 --> 00:30:50.680
He'd say, "Probably north
of the Baltimore now."

00:30:50.680 --> 00:30:51.980
"And where is it now?"

00:30:51.980 --> 00:30:54.580
"Probably near Roslyn."

00:30:54.580 --> 00:30:55.880
"Where is it now?"

00:30:55.880 --> 00:30:59.050
"Probably between Roslyn
and the National Airport."

00:30:59.050 --> 00:31:00.570
"Where is it now?"

00:31:00.570 --> 00:31:03.760
"Oops." "Oops what?"

00:31:03.760 --> 00:31:06.360
"We just lost the bogey,
just lost the target."

00:31:06.360 --> 00:31:08.230
"Where did you lose it?"

00:31:08.230 --> 00:31:12.860
"Somewhere between Pentagon
City and the National Airport."

00:31:12.860 --> 00:31:16.450
And then someone broke into
the phone and said, "Secretary,

00:31:16.450 --> 00:31:20.650
we just got a phone call for an
Arlington County police officer

00:31:20.650 --> 00:31:24.400
who saw an American Airlines
go into the Pentagon."

00:31:24.400 --> 00:31:26.380
So I said, "Monty," I said,

00:31:26.380 --> 00:31:30.550
"that's the third commercial
airliner used as a missile today.

00:31:30.550 --> 00:31:33.020
And we don't know what
the heck is going on.

00:31:33.020 --> 00:31:35.570
The military has something
called stand down.

00:31:35.570 --> 00:31:37.090
We've got to do our own stand down.

00:31:37.090 --> 00:31:40.870
We're going to bring all
the planes down right now."

00:31:40.870 --> 00:31:44.750
And Monty said, "We will bring all
planes down per pilot discretion."

00:31:44.750 --> 00:31:47.840
And I said, "Screw
pilot discretion,"

00:31:47.840 --> 00:31:52.200
because I didn't want a pilot
over let's say Albuquerque

00:31:52.200 --> 00:31:56.470
or Phoenix deciding he'd
just fly into Los Angeles.

00:31:56.470 --> 00:31:57.860
I wanted all the planes down.

00:31:57.860 --> 00:32:03.600
And at that point we had
5,138 planes over the skies.

00:32:03.600 --> 00:32:07.360
And in two hours and 20
minutes we were able to get them

00:32:07.360 --> 00:32:11.890
down all safely and
without incident.

00:32:11.890 --> 00:32:15.450
But that morning, that Tuesday
morning, I pulled three people

00:32:15.450 --> 00:32:19.660
out of ACS -- Aviation
Civil Security.

00:32:19.660 --> 00:32:22.860
I said, "Start putting
together a security regimen

00:32:22.860 --> 00:32:27.160
that we can allow the
airlines to go back up."

00:32:27.160 --> 00:32:31.990
And so they started working
on it, pulled them out of FAA

00:32:31.990 --> 00:32:34.270
and brought them over to my office.

00:32:34.270 --> 00:32:36.140
And they started working on that.

00:32:36.140 --> 00:32:41.420
And it took until Friday for
us to get the new regimen out.

00:32:41.420 --> 00:32:45.440
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: Let me ask you to
look at it now through the eyes

00:32:45.440 --> 00:32:53.620
that we have now where terrorism
has now struck softer targets.

00:32:53.620 --> 00:32:58.990
And do you think that the
reactions were the right one

00:32:58.990 --> 00:33:00.290
on September 11th?

00:33:00.290 --> 00:33:03.690
And what do students and the
rest of us now know better

00:33:03.690 --> 00:33:07.880
as we look back on September 11th?

00:33:07.880 --> 00:33:10.720
Is there a way to better
protect Americans,

00:33:10.720 --> 00:33:12.540
the broader issue of
national security?

00:33:12.540 --> 00:33:13.840
&gt;&gt; Norman Mineta: Well, I
think the fact that the TSA --

00:33:13.840 --> 00:33:19.800
we established TSA
in November of 2001.

00:33:19.800 --> 00:33:23.870
And since then there has
not been a terror incident

00:33:23.870 --> 00:33:29.330
of any major magnitude in
our transportation system.

00:33:29.330 --> 00:33:33.760
The thing that had been
before the case was

00:33:33.760 --> 00:33:37.710
that we allowed the airlines
to do their own security.

00:33:37.710 --> 00:33:39.500
And they would put
it out to low bid,

00:33:39.500 --> 00:33:43.090
and whoever got the low
bid did the security.

00:33:43.090 --> 00:33:45.310
Well, that proved not
to be the case.

00:33:45.310 --> 00:33:50.170
So ACS started putting
together the regimen.

00:33:50.170 --> 00:33:51.470
And what they started out with

00:33:51.470 --> 00:33:55.000
at the very top was no
racial or ethnic profiling.

00:33:55.000 --> 00:34:00.440
And that was the first one
that was in there on the list

00:34:00.440 --> 00:34:03.340
of things that they wrote about.

00:34:03.340 --> 00:34:10.270
Now, on Thursday, September 13th we
had a cabinet meeting of the House

00:34:10.270 --> 00:34:14.440
and Senate Republican
and Democratic leaders.

00:34:14.440 --> 00:34:20.090
And towards the end of that
meeting Congressman David Bonoir

00:34:20.090 --> 00:34:25.580
of Michigan said, "Mr. President,
we have a large population

00:34:25.580 --> 00:34:28.730
of Arab Americans in Michigan.

00:34:28.730 --> 00:34:31.920
And they're very, very
concerned about all this talk

00:34:31.920 --> 00:34:35.710
about keeping Middle
Easterners off airplanes,

00:34:35.710 --> 00:34:38.520
keeping Muslims off airlines.

00:34:38.520 --> 00:34:45.050
And even talk about rounding people
up, putting them into camps."

00:34:45.050 --> 00:34:48.630
And President Bush said, "David,
you're absolutely correct.

00:34:48.630 --> 00:34:53.610
We are equally concerned
about the rhetoric going on.

00:34:53.610 --> 00:34:56.590
And we don't want to have
happen today what happened

00:34:56.590 --> 00:34:59.600
to Norm in 1942."

00:34:59.600 --> 00:35:04.900 position:56%
And you could have hit me with a
feather and knocked me off my chair.

00:35:04.900 --> 00:35:06.200
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: Wow.

00:35:06.200 --> 00:35:07.610
We have so much territory to cover.

00:35:07.610 --> 00:35:10.200
I want to move ahead.

00:35:10.200 --> 00:35:14.580
Alan Simpson, when you look back
at that time and, of course,

00:35:14.580 --> 00:35:19.460
then in 47 days after the
September 11th attacks,

00:35:19.460 --> 00:35:25.020
the United States Congress
passed the Patriot Act.

00:35:25.020 --> 00:35:29.280 position:56%
And you were the judiciary committee
during your time in the Senate.

00:35:29.280 --> 00:35:32.820
Do you think the Patriot
Act was the right next move?

00:35:32.820 --> 00:35:36.400
It's been revised,
obviously, since then.

00:35:36.400 --> 00:35:39.340
But was that reaction
an understandable one

00:35:39.340 --> 00:35:41.520
in terms of national security?

00:35:41.520 --> 00:35:43.950
&gt;&gt; Alan Simpson: Well,
it was responding

00:35:43.950 --> 00:35:48.530
to hysteria and fear and racism.

00:35:48.530 --> 00:35:51.600
And, you know, I always love
it -- I don't love it --

00:35:51.600 --> 00:35:57.450
I'm puzzled when people talk about
what happened in World War II,

00:35:57.450 --> 00:36:01.590
that Earl Warren was
right at the forefront

00:36:01.590 --> 00:36:03.370
of evacuating these people.

00:36:03.370 --> 00:36:08.290 position:56%
And he spent his life on the Supreme
Court trying to expiate his guilt.

00:36:08.290 --> 00:36:11.050
Franklin Roosevelt, one of the
greatest civil libertarians

00:36:11.050 --> 00:36:15.870
of all time, with a great
tragedy the Supreme Court

00:36:15.870 --> 00:36:21.850
of the United States in a 6-3
decision together with the majority

00:36:21.850 --> 00:36:26.320
of William O. Douglas said
this was perfectly okay,

00:36:26.320 --> 00:36:28.920
a military necessity.

00:36:28.920 --> 00:36:32.670
So people said, "Oh, how horrible."

00:36:32.670 --> 00:36:34.490
Well, so what?

00:36:34.490 --> 00:36:39.600
It happened and you
can't unwind history.

00:36:39.600 --> 00:36:42.090
There was a dissent
by a guy named Murphy.

00:36:42.090 --> 00:36:43.390
He was a hack.

00:36:43.390 --> 00:36:44.860
He was a Democrat hack.

00:36:44.860 --> 00:36:48.160
I hate to say that, but he was.

00:36:48.160 --> 00:36:52.620
But he should go down in
history with the Constitution

00:36:52.620 --> 00:36:55.550
and the Gettysburg Address.

00:36:55.550 --> 00:37:01.110
He wrote the dissent, which in
Wyoming terms was essentially

00:37:01.110 --> 00:37:05.500
"Military necessity my ass."

00:37:05.500 --> 00:37:10.170
This was a total violation of the
Constitution of the United States

00:37:10.170 --> 00:37:13.270
of America based on
race and hysteria.

00:37:13.270 --> 00:37:16.130
We are all foreigners
in this country.

00:37:16.130 --> 00:37:22.360
And it isn't that big as on the
wall of the interpretive center

00:37:22.360 --> 00:37:29.080
that dear Norm raised all the
bucks -- I took some of the credit.

00:37:29.080 --> 00:37:32.580
But these things --
I mean, it was done.

00:37:32.580 --> 00:37:37.250
And now, you know, they're
talking about privacy.

00:37:37.250 --> 00:37:41.170
I mean, I have another
twisted view of life:

00:37:41.170 --> 00:37:44.450
I have no privacy, never did.

00:37:44.450 --> 00:37:49.650
I wish they hadn't found out about
some of the stuff but, you know,

00:37:49.650 --> 00:37:52.600
shooting mailboxes and
being on federal probation

00:37:52.600 --> 00:37:56.610
and hitting a cop --
those are not good things.

00:37:56.610 --> 00:38:03.270
But nevertheless, my view is very
simple: What do you got to hide?

00:38:03.270 --> 00:38:08.600 position:56%
And this thing between Apple and
the US is going to get a lot bigger.

00:38:08.600 --> 00:38:09.990
It's going to be like bear meat --

00:38:09.990 --> 00:38:12.970
the more you chew it,
the bigger it gets.

00:38:12.970 --> 00:38:18.540
And at some point you're going to
find guys who are encrypted not

00:38:18.540 --> 00:38:22.220
for going good things in the
world; they're encrypting

00:38:22.220 --> 00:38:26.800
so they can do bad things and
then invent their own coinage

00:38:26.800 --> 00:38:28.770
for God's sake and play bit --

00:38:28.770 --> 00:38:34.030
I mean, the fun and games in my
lifetime in this area are going

00:38:34.030 --> 00:38:39.080 position:56%
to be full zone bullet jacket stuff.

00:38:39.080 --> 00:38:43.330
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: So where are we
