sure that they were published.

00:38:58.530 --> 00:39:00.870
What does the United States do now?

00:39:00.870 --> 00:39:05.060
What should Americans know
about their privacy right now

00:39:05.060 --> 00:39:09.900
and the balance with
national security, Alan?

00:39:09.900 --> 00:39:11.200
&gt;&gt; Alan Simpson: I don't know.

00:39:11.200 --> 00:39:14.910
As I say, it's a puzzler.

00:39:14.910 --> 00:39:17.310
You know, they're waiting
for Snowden.

00:39:17.310 --> 00:39:19.410
They want to extradite him.

00:39:19.410 --> 00:39:21.840
He'd love to come home, though
he ain't going to get home.

00:39:21.840 --> 00:39:27.390
And then there pretty soon
somebody will say as we say

00:39:27.390 --> 00:39:30.440 position:56%
but your shirt, your heart fall out.

00:39:30.440 --> 00:39:32.670
We should have him
back and all that.

00:39:32.670 --> 00:39:34.210
Well, we will bring him back.

00:39:34.210 --> 00:39:39.520
We'll do something in the court
system when he comes back.

00:39:39.520 --> 00:39:40.840
I don't know.

00:39:40.840 --> 00:39:47.130
The whole thing is shot through
with political correctness,

00:39:47.130 --> 00:39:53.720 position:56%
which when I taught at Harvard, I
told my class, "If anyone's enamored

00:39:53.720 --> 00:39:57.670
by political correctness,
you want to get out of here.

00:39:57.670 --> 00:40:01.120
Because we're going to talk about
everything -- the Irish troubles,

00:40:01.120 --> 00:40:04.390
Armenian genocide,
abortion, homosexuality.

00:40:04.390 --> 00:40:08.660
All of this will be talked
about without a muzzle."

00:40:08.660 --> 00:40:11.010
Because I think people who say,

00:40:11.010 --> 00:40:13.490
"I've never had a bad
thought about anything.

00:40:13.490 --> 00:40:17.060
I'm just the sweetest
person on earth

00:40:17.060 --> 00:40:21.090
and never had any bias
or prejudice certainly."

00:40:21.090 --> 00:40:24.200
That's just BS.

00:40:24.200 --> 00:40:28.150 position:56%
So that's going to be one and that's
why this guy Trump is hitting all

00:40:28.150 --> 00:40:30.090
the chords on the <i>Phantom
of the Opera</i>.

00:40:30.090 --> 00:40:32.870
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: Trump, who is this?

00:40:32.870 --> 00:40:35.810
&gt;&gt; Alan Simpson: He's not my guy.

00:40:35.810 --> 00:40:38.020
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: Mr. Secretary?

00:40:38.020 --> 00:40:39.690
&gt;&gt; Norman Mineta: Well, I was
on the Intelligence Committee

00:40:39.690 --> 00:40:45.190
when we wrote the FISA, the Foreign
Intelligence Surveillance Act.

00:40:45.190 --> 00:40:50.050
In there, there was a
requirement that the NSA had

00:40:50.050 --> 00:40:55.250
to get a search warrant to
tap the lines of a US citizen,

00:40:55.250 --> 00:40:59.060
go to a three-judge tribunal
to get a search warrant.

00:40:59.060 --> 00:41:02.950
Now, that was eliminated
in the Patriot Act.

00:41:02.950 --> 00:41:05.810
And so the protection there

00:41:05.810 --> 00:41:12.900
about what can the government
have access to wasn't there.

00:41:12.900 --> 00:41:15.920
And that bothered me.

00:41:15.920 --> 00:41:19.670
And I remember the
administration had asked me

00:41:19.670 --> 00:41:22.440 position:56%
to help get the Patriot Act through.

00:41:22.440 --> 00:41:24.530
I said no, I couldn't help them

00:41:24.530 --> 00:41:27.870
because they had eliminated
the three-judge panel

00:41:27.870 --> 00:41:30.850
when they rewrote the FISA act.

00:41:30.850 --> 00:41:40.530
And so I think there has to be the
kind of protection to citizens,

00:41:40.530 --> 00:41:47.180
even with the national security
as extreme as it could be.

00:41:47.180 --> 00:41:52.510
And otherwise, you
know, the whole --

00:41:52.510 --> 00:41:57.610
the thing I couldn't understand
was on September 11th was sort

00:41:57.610 --> 00:42:01.440
of reliving the evacuation of '42.

00:42:01.440 --> 00:42:05.180
Because here you had
the media people saying,

00:42:05.180 --> 00:42:07.680
"Round them up, keep
them off planes."

00:42:07.680 --> 00:42:13.290
And so, I mean, even the
president said, "We don't want

00:42:13.290 --> 00:42:16.320
to have happen today what
happened to Norm in '42."

00:42:16.320 --> 00:42:23.660
And then he met with a large
group of Arab-Americans,

00:42:23.660 --> 00:42:32.300
Muslims at the Islamic
Study Center on Mass Avenue

00:42:32.300 --> 00:42:35.480
on Monday, September 17th.

00:42:35.480 --> 00:42:39.960
And he said to them, "We know
who did that last Tuesday.

00:42:39.960 --> 00:42:43.000
They were not loyal Arab-Americans.

00:42:43.000 --> 00:42:47.500
They were not faithful
followers of Islam.

00:42:47.500 --> 00:42:48.890
They were terrorists.

00:42:48.890 --> 00:42:51.010
And we're going to go after them."

00:42:51.010 --> 00:42:53.860
And the same thing happened
at the end of September,

00:42:53.860 --> 00:42:59.440
there was someone shot and killed
-- a man who owned a gas station.

00:42:59.440 --> 00:43:00.970
It was a minimart.

00:43:00.970 --> 00:43:02.600
And when they apprehended
the killer,

00:43:02.600 --> 00:43:04.260
they said, "Why did you kill him?"

00:43:04.260 --> 00:43:07.490
He said, "Because he
looked like the enemy."

00:43:07.490 --> 00:43:09.700
The fellow was a Sikh.

00:43:09.700 --> 00:43:11.000
And he had --

00:43:11.000 --> 00:43:12.300
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: The turban.

00:43:12.300 --> 00:43:16.460
&gt;&gt; Norman Mineta: He had facial
hair, he had leg bindings.

00:43:16.460 --> 00:43:20.180
Said simply because he
looked like the enemy."

00:43:20.180 --> 00:43:22.510
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: What part
of government really has

00:43:22.510 --> 00:43:24.420
to take the lead on security?

00:43:24.420 --> 00:43:26.760
Is it the Executive?

00:43:26.760 --> 00:43:31.210
Is Congress uniquely unsuited to
really grapple with these issues?

00:43:31.210 --> 00:43:33.420
Should it really be
left to the courts,

00:43:33.420 --> 00:43:35.890
the ultimate resort the courts?

00:43:35.890 --> 00:43:37.460
Who in government?

00:43:37.460 --> 00:43:40.390
&gt;&gt; Norman Mineta: Well,
it requires --

00:43:40.390 --> 00:43:49.120
the Executive part of our
government still requires laws

00:43:49.120 --> 00:43:53.410
by which it gets the
authority to do something.

00:43:53.410 --> 00:44:00.720
So as in the Transportation
Security Act of November 17, 2001,

00:44:00.720 --> 00:44:06.730
Congress created TSA
and gave us the --

00:44:06.730 --> 00:44:13.920
there were 36 mandates in the
law as to what we had to do.

00:44:13.920 --> 00:44:17.760
So you still had to have
the Congress involved in it.

00:44:17.760 --> 00:44:23.320
At the time Congress wanted to have
the security done by contractors.

00:44:23.320 --> 00:44:28.000
And I maintained that the
contractors didn't do their job.

00:44:28.000 --> 00:44:30.430
And I wanted them as
federal employees

00:44:30.430 --> 00:44:36.010
so that regardless whether you got
on the plane in Chicago, Dallas,

00:44:36.010 --> 00:44:42.420 position:56%
Fort Worth, or [inaudible] Iowa,
you were going to have the same kind

00:44:42.420 --> 00:44:46.110
of level of security being applied.

00:44:46.110 --> 00:44:50.320
So we were finally
able to get Congress.

00:44:50.320 --> 00:44:53.570
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: These
things are a federal job.

00:44:53.570 --> 00:44:55.480
Immigration is a federal
responsibility.

00:44:55.480 --> 00:44:56.780 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Norman Mineta: That's our next --

00:44:56.780 --> 00:44:58.460
&gt;&gt; Alan Simpson: Not a
state-by-state responsibility.

00:44:58.460 --> 00:45:03.010
But if you have a Congress
that won't function on an issue

00:45:03.010 --> 00:45:07.220
and they're not functioning on the
issue, then the president's going

00:45:07.220 --> 00:45:08.610
to come in with executive order,

00:45:08.610 --> 00:45:11.990
which is exactly what has
happened with immigration.

00:45:11.990 --> 00:45:17.390
And when we did an immigration
bill back in '86, bipartisan,

00:45:17.390 --> 00:45:23.010 position:56%
big votes both sides, it didn't work
because the right and the left --

00:45:23.010 --> 00:45:28.060 position:56%
Grover Norquist rode in on his white
horse, I remember, and his robes.

00:45:28.060 --> 00:45:31.210
He was kind of like
Paul Revere in reverse.

00:45:31.210 --> 00:45:33.410
[ Laughter ]

00:45:33.410 --> 00:45:39.830
And then also the ACLU
rose in abject anguish

00:45:39.830 --> 00:45:42.780
and called what we had in there --

00:45:42.780 --> 00:45:48.650
we got to have a more secure
identifier to protect the employer.

00:45:48.650 --> 00:45:52.370
And they took it out because the
national rage created by the left

00:45:52.370 --> 00:45:56.800
and the right was that that
was a national ID card.

00:45:56.800 --> 00:45:58.210
Boy, that's a way to kill stuff

00:45:58.210 --> 00:46:02.710
around this joint:
Invent a flash word.

00:46:02.710 --> 00:46:04.810
National ID card.

00:46:04.810 --> 00:46:08.170
Now they're talking about
retina scans and fingerprints.

00:46:08.170 --> 00:46:13.020
And nobody's written any kind of an
editorial about the slippery slope.

00:46:13.020 --> 00:46:15.400
I mean, you know, it is madness.

00:46:15.400 --> 00:46:20.540
But if Congress won't function,
any president is going to function.

00:46:20.540 --> 00:46:23.490
And then if that doesn't
work, the court will function.

00:46:23.490 --> 00:46:25.660
And that's the way that works.

00:46:25.660 --> 00:46:28.270 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: We are going to open
