start with a question submitted

00:49:05.060 --> 00:49:08.540
from the students in Hawaii
who are watching online.

00:49:08.540 --> 00:49:12.580
One of the students has a question
about American values and states

00:49:12.580 --> 00:49:15.500
that American values are
what makes us unique.

00:49:15.500 --> 00:49:18.570
&gt;&gt; I had a mortar platoon
in the army

00:49:18.570 --> 00:49:20.550
and I'm not getting -- it's blurry.

00:49:20.550 --> 00:49:21.850
&gt;&gt; John Van Oudenaren:
I'll repeat the question.

00:49:21.850 --> 00:49:23.150
&gt;&gt; Yeah, please.

00:49:23.150 --> 00:49:25.070 position:56%
&gt;&gt; John Van Oudenaren: The question
about American values which are seen

00:49:25.070 --> 00:49:28.390
around the world as one of the
great things about this country.

00:49:28.390 --> 00:49:31.620
The question is: How do
you each think we are doing

00:49:31.620 --> 00:49:34.880
in role modeling our values
in the face of threats?

00:49:34.880 --> 00:49:38.140
And what more do we need
to do to enhance security

00:49:38.140 --> 00:49:41.860 position:56%
without undermining what many
internationally find most attractive

00:49:41.860 --> 00:49:43.390
in the US?

00:49:43.390 --> 00:49:47.500
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: Could you hear
part of that, Secretary Mineta?

00:49:47.500 --> 00:49:50.220
What do we need for
national security

00:49:50.220 --> 00:49:57.680
that doesn't violate our sense
of privacy rights, of the honor?

00:49:57.680 --> 00:50:02.090
What was the other phrase
that the student used?

00:50:02.090 --> 00:50:03.390
&gt;&gt; John Van Oudenaren: Integrity.

00:50:03.390 --> 00:50:04.690
Integrity.

00:50:04.690 --> 00:50:07.200
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: The
integrity of Americans.

00:50:07.200 --> 00:50:09.690
Now, that's a -- it's
a great question,

00:50:09.690 --> 00:50:13.060
but it's also a very tall order.

00:50:13.060 --> 00:50:14.860
&gt;&gt; Norman Mineta: Next question.

00:50:14.860 --> 00:50:17.490
[ Laughter ]

00:50:17.490 --> 00:50:23.350
Well, I think first we
start with common sense.

00:50:23.350 --> 00:50:25.050
But I think we also
[inaudible] baked

00:50:25.050 --> 00:50:33.150
into there is the increased need
for the use of technology in terms

00:50:33.150 --> 00:50:38.530
of being able to do things today
from a security perspective.

00:50:38.530 --> 00:50:41.080
And I think there are
ways of doing that.

00:50:41.080 --> 00:50:44.750
And I think -- but as
Alan just pointed out,

00:50:44.750 --> 00:50:49.350
the Apple case is a good
example of where you do get

00:50:49.350 --> 00:50:52.580
into issues involving technology.

00:50:52.580 --> 00:50:57.160
But I think what we
have done in TSA --

00:50:57.160 --> 00:51:01.720
and one thing that TSA
does is they're looking

00:51:01.720 --> 00:51:04.850
at that security issue every day.

00:51:04.850 --> 00:51:12.650
I mean, in December of 2001, we
had to deal with the shoe bomber.

00:51:12.650 --> 00:51:18.930
And then we had to deal with --
usually explosives are solids.

00:51:18.930 --> 00:51:24.760
But by 2003 we were
dealing with liquids.

00:51:24.760 --> 00:51:29.390
So now we were dealing
with containers

00:51:29.390 --> 00:51:33.770
of less than 3.0 fluid ounces.

00:51:33.770 --> 00:51:38.130
So but it's something that's
just changing every day.

00:51:38.130 --> 00:51:40.650 position:56%
And I think that's what is required.

00:51:40.650 --> 00:51:41.950
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: Senator?

00:51:41.950 --> 00:51:44.680
&gt;&gt; Alan Simpson: There's got to
be something that you do that has

00:51:44.680 --> 00:51:46.850
to do with identification.

00:51:46.850 --> 00:51:49.090
Without getting into
the horror story,

00:51:49.090 --> 00:51:52.350
something that would be
presented at the time of --

00:51:52.350 --> 00:51:54.970
it wouldn't be carried
on your person,

00:51:54.970 --> 00:51:59.640
it wouldn't be whatever,
all the horror stories.

00:51:59.640 --> 00:52:03.690 position:56%
But it would be something that you
presented at the time of employment.

00:52:03.690 --> 00:52:07.410
And it would be presented
by bald white guys

00:52:07.410 --> 00:52:09.480
like me, as well as others.

00:52:09.480 --> 00:52:12.200
The issue always comes up
we're just going to ask

00:52:12.200 --> 00:52:14.200
that of people who look foreign.

00:52:14.200 --> 00:52:15.920
Well, that's absurd.

00:52:15.920 --> 00:52:17.630
Nobody's for that.

00:52:17.630 --> 00:52:20.450
But you have to do something
that has a universal --

00:52:20.450 --> 00:52:23.920
at one time we talked about
having the maiden name

00:52:23.920 --> 00:52:27.530
of a person's mother
on the back of a card.

00:52:27.530 --> 00:52:29.160
Well, that will cost trillions.

00:52:29.160 --> 00:52:31.700
Well, you know, we've
all heard that one.

00:52:31.700 --> 00:52:36.010
And then to put something
like a slide card like you do

00:52:36.010 --> 00:52:43.940
in Macy's somewhere or something
that has to be done by everybody.

00:52:43.940 --> 00:52:46.250
And at that point it
will be intrusive;

00:52:46.250 --> 00:52:48.620
it will be reported as intrusive.

00:52:48.620 --> 00:52:53.660 position:56%
But at some point in time there will
be one of these boobs of any color,

00:52:53.660 --> 00:52:55.040
or shape, or form that's going

00:52:55.040 --> 00:52:58.480
to ignite a shoe box
somewhere in this country.

00:52:58.480 --> 00:53:02.010
And then we'll all stand around and
blink like a frog in a hailstorm.

00:53:02.010 --> 00:53:03.580
[ Laughter ]

00:53:03.580 --> 00:53:07.300
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: Next question.

00:53:07.300 --> 00:53:10.980
&gt;&gt; John Van Oudenaren: There are a
couple of questions about refugees

00:53:10.980 --> 00:53:14.140
and what the United
States should do in light

00:53:14.140 --> 00:53:18.810
of the current refugee situation
in Syria, Iraq, Afghanistan,

00:53:18.810 --> 00:53:22.850
and how we might protect
our national security

00:53:22.850 --> 00:53:24.870
and accept refugees
from these countries?

00:53:24.870 --> 00:53:27.890
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: Good questions
on accepting refugees.

00:53:27.890 --> 00:53:32.370
Pope Francis came back to
the Vatican from a visit

00:53:32.370 --> 00:53:35.480
in Greece bringing
12 Syrian refugees.

00:53:35.480 --> 00:53:37.960
I don't know who vetted them,
but they got on the plane

00:53:37.960 --> 00:53:40.910
and they came back [inaudible]
three families, I believe.

00:53:40.910 --> 00:53:42.910 position:56%
There are some Americans communities

00:53:42.910 --> 00:53:45.980
that don't want Syrian
refugees anywhere near them.

00:53:45.980 --> 00:53:50.540
There are some churches and
groups and community groups

00:53:50.540 --> 00:53:53.340
who have welcomed them and
said, "Let us help you."

00:53:53.340 --> 00:53:57.430
Do you, either of you
worry about the flood

00:53:57.430 --> 00:54:01.100
of Syrian refugees coming
into the United States?

00:54:01.100 --> 00:54:08.010
And since the screening would be
so hard to do, is that a weak point

00:54:08.010 --> 00:54:10.960
in the United States' security?

00:54:10.960 --> 00:54:13.690
&gt;&gt; Alan Simpson: Well, any
weak point is a weak point

00:54:13.690 --> 00:54:15.450
if you don't understand
the difference

00:54:15.450 --> 00:54:18.730
between an economic migrant, and
guy that just wants to get the hell

00:54:18.730 --> 00:54:21.420
out of his country, and a refugee.

00:54:21.420 --> 00:54:26.670
A refugee is something that is
cherished and then they can go

00:54:26.670 --> 00:54:28.950
to sanctuary, which
is a cherished thing.

00:54:28.950 --> 00:54:32.680
You can't be an economic migrant
that just doesn't like his country

00:54:32.680 --> 00:54:36.110
or decides to hop on a
plane and close his shop

00:54:36.110 --> 00:54:38.460
because his neighbor got shot.

00:54:38.460 --> 00:54:39.760
That is not a refugee.

00:54:39.760 --> 00:54:41.820
I know, don't throw
anything, please.

00:54:41.820 --> 00:54:43.630
I've been here.

00:54:43.630 --> 00:54:46.280 position:56%
So you have to do this case by case.

00:54:46.280 --> 00:54:49.750
And it's tedious but it works.

00:54:49.750 --> 00:54:54.940 position:56%
But the economic migrant is flooding
the world because when you're

00:54:54.940 --> 00:54:58.400
out of food and water and
you have a lovely family,

00:54:58.400 --> 00:54:59.840
you're going to start walking.

00:54:59.840 --> 00:55:02.830
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: And you've lost
your home in Syria because of --

00:55:02.830 --> 00:55:04.130
&gt;&gt; Alan Simpson: That's right.

00:55:04.130 --> 00:55:06.370
But a refugee -- a real refugee --

00:55:06.370 --> 00:55:10.950
the minute their foot hits
the next spot out, that's it.

00:55:10.950 --> 00:55:13.160
You don't get to pick
where you want to go.

00:55:13.160 --> 00:55:16.380
I know that sound nasty,
I know it does.

00:55:16.380 --> 00:55:20.630
But once you're a refugee
or seeking asylum --

00:55:20.630 --> 00:55:24.060
that's the same in a sense, you're
there or you're not there --

00:55:24.060 --> 00:55:28.160
once you hit that next
piece of land where isn't

00:55:28.160 --> 00:55:29.830
that oppression, that's it.

00:55:29.830 --> 00:55:32.790
You cannot then say, "I want
to go to the United States.

00:55:32.790 --> 00:55:34.220
I want to go to Germany.

00:55:34.220 --> 00:55:35.520
I want to go to France.

00:55:35.520 --> 00:55:36.900
I want to go to Israel."

00:55:36.900 --> 00:55:38.260
It's not the way it works.

00:55:38.260 --> 00:55:42.200
And boy, you start playing that and
the violin music will overcome you.

00:55:42.200 --> 00:55:44.630
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: Do you
want to add in on that?

00:55:44.630 --> 00:55:47.300
&gt;&gt; Norman Mineta: The
status of refugee,

00:55:47.300 --> 00:55:52.620
the investigation that's required
of that is very, very intensive.

00:55:52.620 --> 00:56:01.910 position:56%
And so it is very difficult, really,
to be I think vetted as a refugee.

00:56:01.910 --> 00:56:08.820
And I think to the extent that
they are vetted as refugees,

00:56:08.820 --> 00:56:13.540
I would say they're safe
and clear to come in.

00:56:13.540 --> 00:56:16.740
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: Do you think
that the current system

00:56:16.740 --> 00:56:21.280
for vetting refugees and
those who are trying to come

00:56:21.280 --> 00:56:23.310
into the United States is adequate?

00:56:23.310 --> 00:56:24.610
&gt;&gt; Norman Mineta: Absolutely.

00:56:24.610 --> 00:56:29.070
Because I think it requires the
personal signature of the Secretary

00:56:29.070 --> 00:56:34.610
of Homeland Security and --

00:56:34.610 --> 00:56:36.330 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Alan Simpson: Secretary of State.

00:56:36.330 --> 00:56:37.630
&gt;&gt; Norman Mineta: Secretary
of State.

00:56:37.630 --> 00:56:39.140
&gt;&gt; Alan Simpson: George
Shultz, who was very helpful

00:56:39.140 --> 00:56:41.010
to Kennedy and I on that.

00:56:41.010 --> 00:56:42.310
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: Yep.

00:56:42.310 --> 00:56:44.260
Another question?

00:56:44.260 --> 00:56:45.910
&gt;&gt; John Van Oudenaren: There
are a number of questions

00:56:45.910 --> 00:56:48.640
about privacy and surveillance.

00:56:48.640 --> 00:56:52.350
And one of the students from the
University of Hawaii actually asked

00:56:52.350 --> 00:56:56.080
if the surveillance
measures employed now

00:56:56.080 --> 00:57:03.200
by the NSA create a sort
of virtual internment camp.

00:57:03.200 --> 00:57:05.580
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: That's interesting.

00:57:05.580 --> 00:57:13.190
Do you think that the kind of
response to Edward Snowden's leaks

00:57:13.190 --> 00:57:17.780
and the kind of surveillance
-- the broader surveillance,

00:57:17.780 --> 00:57:21.490
whether it went through
the FISA court or not --

00:57:21.490 --> 00:57:26.850
almost levees the threat or
the feeling of an interment

00:57:26.850 --> 00:57:32.820
and a restriction that impinges too
much on Americans' privacy rights?

00:57:32.820 --> 00:57:36.740
&gt;&gt; Norman Mineta: Well, when I
was Secretary of Transportation,

00:57:36.740 --> 00:57:45.820
I did ban -- not ban --
we were not processing any

00:57:45.820 --> 00:57:49.290
of the applications as
it related to drones.

00:57:49.290 --> 00:57:53.080
Because I thought the
invasion of civil --

00:57:53.080 --> 00:57:56.900
or just privacy was tremendous.

00:57:56.900 --> 00:58:06.250
In fact, just a month ago, my
wife and I and another couple were

00:58:06.250 --> 00:58:11.100
at a restaurant in San
Francisco along the Bay.

00:58:11.100 --> 00:58:17.710
And here comes a drone and it just
went back and forth in front of us.

00:58:17.710 --> 00:58:22.120
And, you know, I was
thinking "Whose drone is that?

00:58:22.120 --> 00:58:24.060
What are they looking for?"

00:58:24.060 --> 00:58:29.830
And I thought back to 2003

00:58:29.830 --> 00:58:34.540
when I was saying we're
not going to allow drones.

00:58:34.540 --> 00:58:38.110
And so --

00:58:38.110 --> 00:58:39.560
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: And
now they almost --

00:58:39.560 --> 00:58:42.370
that genie seems out of
the bottle, isn't it?

00:58:42.370 --> 00:58:43.670
&gt;&gt; Norman Mineta: Oh, it is.

00:58:43.670 --> 00:58:45.610
It really is.

00:58:45.610 --> 00:58:47.500
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: Senator?

00:58:47.500 --> 00:58:48.800
&gt;&gt; Alan Simpson: Well,

00:58:48.800 --> 00:58:55.490
these technical things now are
quite dazzling for us old coots --

00:58:55.490 --> 00:58:59.080
Twitter, tweety, Instagram.

00:58:59.080 --> 00:59:01.910
You know, it's amazing.

00:59:01.910 --> 00:59:06.990
And then they're talking about some
new thing that I can't remember.

00:59:06.990 --> 00:59:08.290
They're all new.

00:59:08.290 --> 00:59:14.060 position:56%
But the point is the invasion -- if
anyone believes that there's privacy

00:59:14.060 --> 00:59:16.720
in America, they're
in a dream world.

00:59:16.720 --> 00:59:19.680
There was a program -- I
don't remember what it was --

00:59:19.680 --> 00:59:24.550
and they had a couple from
Dubuque or Boone, Iowa or Cheyenne

00:59:24.550 --> 00:59:27.480
and they said, "How much do
you think we know about you?"

00:59:27.480 --> 00:59:30.630
And they said, "We've never
done anything important,

00:59:30.630 --> 00:59:32.180
so you don't know too much."

00:59:32.180 --> 00:59:36.280
And they ran up on the screen
and man, they knew lots

00:59:36.280 --> 00:59:40.530
about those two people
through their media habits,

00:59:40.530 --> 00:59:41.830
through their buying habits --

00:59:41.830 --> 00:59:43.150
they're buying stuff
on the Internet,

00:59:43.150 --> 00:59:45.400
you're answering those
little questions,

00:59:45.400 --> 00:59:47.570
or you're get that
stuff in the mail.

00:59:47.570 --> 00:59:51.950
And they know everything you
would never imagine they know

00:59:51.950 --> 00:59:53.250
about all of us.

00:59:53.250 --> 01:00:00.380
So this plea for privacy and then
to have it upheld by the media,

01:00:00.380 --> 01:00:02.490 position:56%
crying for a right of privacy, well,

01:00:02.490 --> 01:00:07.830
they're the greatest
invaders of anybody's privacy.

01:00:07.830 --> 01:00:10.940
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: Real
quickly for each of you,

01:00:10.940 --> 01:00:14.490
should Apple have immediately
done what it could

01:00:14.490 --> 01:00:18.040
to help the federal government
on cracking that phone?

01:00:18.040 --> 01:00:20.010
&gt;&gt; Alan Simpson: You
take that Norm, quick.

01:00:20.010 --> 01:00:24.360
&gt;&gt; Norman Mineta: I think so,
but I'm on the minority on that.

01:00:24.360 --> 01:00:27.260
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: You think
that Apple should have?

01:00:27.260 --> 01:00:30.480
&gt;&gt; Norman Mineta: Oh, they
should have been much more open

01:00:30.480 --> 01:00:33.520
about dealing with that issue.

01:00:33.520 --> 01:00:35.610
But I'm a real minority on that.

01:00:35.610 --> 01:00:36.910
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: Okay, okay.

01:00:36.910 --> 01:00:38.390
&gt;&gt; Alan Simpson: But I
think that's the view

01:00:38.390 --> 01:00:41.860
of older people: What
do you got to hide?

01:00:41.860 --> 01:00:46.420
And this -- who wouldn't want
to know what's on the cell phone

01:00:46.420 --> 01:00:52.160
of a couple of cooks that destroyed
14 human beings and were in contact

01:00:52.160 --> 01:00:53.980
with people maybe around the world?

01:00:53.980 --> 01:00:56.060
Who wouldn't want to know that?

01:00:56.060 --> 01:01:01.330
It was like the old <i>Stanford
Daily</i> case; do you remember that?

01:01:01.330 --> 01:01:04.940
They had a riot at Stanford and
the <i>Stanford Daily</i> paper --

01:01:04.940 --> 01:01:08.400
the student paper -- knew
who had been involved.

01:01:08.400 --> 01:01:10.780
And the cops wanted
that information.

01:01:10.780 --> 01:01:15.280
It went clear to the US Supreme
Court and Justice Wyatt said,

01:01:15.280 --> 01:01:17.740
"You can't have that
kind of protection.

01:01:17.740 --> 01:01:19.600
They want to know who did this.

01:01:19.600 --> 01:01:23.010
You can't pull this game of,
you know, the right of privacy

01:01:23.010 --> 01:01:25.640
and protection of source
and all this stuff."

01:01:25.640 --> 01:01:30.300
And when you have murderous
people in the world,

01:01:30.300 --> 01:01:35.270
these other things sound good
and they are part of America,

01:01:35.270 --> 01:01:38.520 position:56%
but don't think America is
diminished when we're trying to wipe

01:01:38.520 --> 01:01:41.470
out people who hate our guts.

01:01:41.470 --> 01:01:43.490
I don't know, sick idea.

01:01:43.490 --> 01:01:44.790
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: I want
to make sure we have time

01:01:44.790 --> 01:01:49.870
for a few more questions from the
audience and from the students.

01:01:49.870 --> 01:01:51.820
&gt;&gt; John Van Oudenaren:
Another question from Hawaii,

01:01:51.820 --> 01:01:54.810
actually a couple questions
from Hawaii ask

01:01:54.810 --> 01:02:01.120
about providing military
equipment to local police forces.

01:02:01.120 --> 01:02:02.860
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: Providing
what to local?

01:02:02.860 --> 01:02:04.160
&gt;&gt; Military equipment.

01:02:04.160 --> 01:02:05.460
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: Equipment.

01:02:05.460 --> 01:02:07.560
&gt;&gt; John Van Oudenaren: To police
forces, especially in light

01:02:07.560 --> 01:02:12.010
of what occurred in Ferguson and on
Staten Island with Michael Brown,

01:02:12.010 --> 01:02:14.880
is how do we balance security

01:02:14.880 --> 01:02:17.440
in those instances
with civil liberties?

01:02:17.440 --> 01:02:21.450
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: Well, obviously in
the cases after Ferguson, Missouri

01:02:21.450 --> 01:02:25.610
and in some other communities
-- Baltimore had some riots --

01:02:25.610 --> 01:02:28.570
some people have objected
to what looked

01:02:28.570 --> 01:02:31.490
like a huge military operation.

01:02:31.490 --> 01:02:34.560
And isn't that really up
to the local community,

01:02:34.560 --> 01:02:36.270
the local law enforcement?

01:02:36.270 --> 01:02:41.140 position:56%
Someday they might need that armored
troop carrier and the water canons.

01:02:41.140 --> 01:02:43.510
Sometimes they may overuse it.

01:02:43.510 --> 01:02:46.990
But should local police
departments have access to quite

01:02:46.990 --> 01:02:49.480
so much military fire power?

01:02:49.480 --> 01:02:53.600
&gt;&gt; Alan Simpson: I
think that's a point.

01:02:53.600 --> 01:02:55.430
Both of us were in the military.

01:02:55.430 --> 01:02:58.790
And, you know, we weren't
trained to hand out daisies;

01:02:58.790 --> 01:03:02.140
we were trained to kill people.

01:03:02.140 --> 01:03:07.130
And so I do think that when you
have an armored personnel carrier

01:03:07.130 --> 01:03:12.570
in the midst of a city and you
unload a squad from the back of it,

01:03:12.570 --> 01:03:15.920
if those are things
that I knew how to run,

01:03:15.920 --> 01:03:18.250
I think that's highly intimidating.

01:03:18.250 --> 01:03:22.840
But that came from that
funding source where they said,

01:03:22.840 --> 01:03:28.520
"We got this leftover stuff and all
you have to do is apply for it."

01:03:28.520 --> 01:03:32.980
And I think it has to be
rather frightening when you're

01:03:32.980 --> 01:03:37.070
in the street and alone
or with or without arms.

01:03:37.070 --> 01:03:40.060
I don't know, I think there's
real truth to the military.

01:03:40.060 --> 01:03:42.790
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: And some of those
incidents were racial incidents

01:03:42.790 --> 01:03:48.200
at a local level as
opposed to San Bernardino

01:03:48.200 --> 01:03:52.510
where it was clearly an attack
by people who had a political

01:03:52.510 --> 01:03:58.660
or radical ideology that they were
trying to strike at a soft target.

01:03:58.660 --> 01:03:59.960
&gt;&gt; Norman Mineta: Yeah.

01:03:59.960 --> 01:04:02.410
Having been mayor, I'm
not sure that I would want

01:04:02.410 --> 01:04:07.850
to have a police force
with that equipment.

01:04:07.850 --> 01:04:13.350
The whole issue of
policing is really --

01:04:13.350 --> 01:04:19.360
the whole issue is how do
you relate to the community?

01:04:19.360 --> 01:04:24.760
When I was mayor, police were
starting to put helmets on.

01:04:24.760 --> 01:04:27.500
And I finally said to
our chief of police,

01:04:27.500 --> 01:04:34.250
"I'm not sure I want our police
with these hard helmets on.

01:04:34.250 --> 01:04:35.550
They don't smile.

01:04:35.550 --> 01:04:41.610
They can't be friendly-looking
just having these hardhats on."

01:04:41.610 --> 01:04:48.550
And so we were one of
the first ones after --

01:04:48.550 --> 01:04:54.510
and I negotiated this
with our police union --

01:04:54.510 --> 01:05:02.420
and so we took the caps or the
hardhats off of our police.

01:05:02.420 --> 01:05:06.290
We were also one of
the first departments

01:05:06.290 --> 01:05:11.230
to require psychological
testing of applicants.

01:05:11.230 --> 01:05:13.730
And this was in 1973.

01:05:13.730 --> 01:05:21.200
And the -- at the time the
police, the union really came

01:05:21.200 --> 01:05:23.960
down on me saying, you know,
"You think we're all psychotics?"

01:05:23.960 --> 01:05:25.260
And I said.

01:05:25.260 --> 01:05:26.560
"No, not at all.

01:05:26.560 --> 01:05:29.590
Today every department
across the country is doing

01:05:29.590 --> 01:05:31.320
psychological testing."

01:05:31.320 --> 01:05:34.250
But it's really for
their own protection.

01:05:34.250 --> 01:05:41.580
For the same thing with the
military type of equipment,

01:05:41.580 --> 01:05:44.450 position:56%
I don't think it's really necessary.

01:05:44.450 --> 01:05:51.210
Even in Katrina when General Honore
came in with the military forces

01:05:51.210 --> 01:05:55.640
and they were there with their
weapons out, and he was running up

01:05:55.640 --> 01:06:00.060
and down the street telling
people to get their weapons up.

01:06:00.060 --> 01:06:05.280
Not to, you know, point
them at the mass of people.

01:06:05.280 --> 01:06:09.740
And General Honore really, I think,

01:06:09.740 --> 01:06:13.390
did a great service
in lifting those.

01:06:13.390 --> 01:06:19.280 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Alan Simpson: But there's this
wonderful man that uses common sense

01:06:19.280 --> 01:06:24.070
and doesn't get caught up in the
grinder of emotion, fear, guilt,

01:06:24.070 --> 01:06:28.870
and racism or try to have a press
conference every few minutes

01:06:28.870 --> 01:06:30.490
to blow your own horn.

01:06:30.490 --> 01:06:35.760
This is happening and people
are so confounded by it.

01:06:35.760 --> 01:06:37.290
Where is common sense?

01:06:37.290 --> 01:06:38.590
What happened?

01:06:38.590 --> 01:06:41.330
The most uncommon thing
is common sense.

01:06:41.330 --> 01:06:44.320
And when Norm was mayor
I happened to know

01:06:44.320 --> 01:06:48.910 position:56%
that he would gather people together
and talk and say, "Where are we?

01:06:48.910 --> 01:06:50.210
What are we doing?"

01:06:50.210 --> 01:06:51.510
That's what he did in Congress.

01:06:51.510 --> 01:06:52.810
That's how he got --

01:06:52.810 --> 01:06:55.260
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: Does
that work in 2016?

01:06:55.260 --> 01:06:58.040
&gt;&gt; Alan Simpson: Not when you've
got everybody stereotyped.

01:06:58.040 --> 01:07:00.990
I can tell you that here we
did this piece of work --

01:07:00.990 --> 01:07:02.290
don't throw anything --

01:07:02.290 --> 01:07:05.250
it was called the National
Commission on Deficit and Debt.

01:07:05.250 --> 01:07:09.350
We got five Democrats, five
Republicans, one Independent.

01:07:09.350 --> 01:07:11.140
That's 60%.

01:07:11.140 --> 01:07:13.870 position:56%
And then say, "Well, who was on it?"

01:07:13.870 --> 01:07:15.840
Well, Dick Durbin.

01:07:15.840 --> 01:07:17.880
Dick Durbin?

01:07:17.880 --> 01:07:19.580
That Commie from Illinois?

01:07:19.580 --> 01:07:26.050
Is that what you -- I
said, "Well, Tom Corburn."

01:07:26.050 --> 01:07:27.350
Tom Corburn?

01:07:27.350 --> 01:07:29.390
That guy from -- that
Republican from Oklahoma?

01:07:29.390 --> 01:07:31.800
That's your country today.

01:07:31.800 --> 01:07:34.370
People don't dislike
somebody, they hate them

01:07:34.370 --> 01:07:36.950
and they got them pegged
as a Democrat.

01:07:36.950 --> 01:07:40.560
They hate Obama, they hate
[inaudible], they hate Trump,

01:07:40.560 --> 01:07:42.720
they hate Cruz, they hate Hillary.

01:07:42.720 --> 01:07:44.240
It's not dislike.

01:07:44.240 --> 01:07:45.540
It's disgusting.

01:07:45.540 --> 01:07:48.270
And hatred corrodes the
container it's carried in.

01:07:48.270 --> 01:07:51.680 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: So tell the
students especially who are watching

01:07:51.680 --> 01:07:56.640
from Hawaii, how do Americans
bring the country back

01:07:56.640 --> 01:07:58.740
from that kind of atmosphere?

01:07:58.740 --> 01:08:00.220
&gt;&gt; Alan Simpson: Well, they
could get off their butt

01:08:00.220 --> 01:08:02.430
and get in the game.

01:08:02.430 --> 01:08:05.680
Because if you really want
to do something, pick a party

01:08:05.680 --> 01:08:10.620 position:56%
and become a precinct committee man
-- that's the lowest form of amoeba.

01:08:10.620 --> 01:08:17.380
Or you could be a precinct
committee man or woman.

01:08:17.380 --> 01:08:18.980
You could run for the school board.

01:08:18.980 --> 01:08:20.360
I brought Norm to Harvard.

01:08:20.360 --> 01:08:22.750
I couldn't have got into Harvard
if I had picked the locks.

01:08:22.750 --> 01:08:26.290
But I told him, "Get up here

01:08:26.290 --> 01:08:29.370
because they're protesting
the [inaudible] thing

01:08:29.370 --> 01:08:31.010
down in [inaudible]."

01:08:31.010 --> 01:08:34.380
He came and he said,
"Anybody can carry a placard.

01:08:34.380 --> 01:08:36.910
Anybody can stand in the
street with a poster.

01:08:36.910 --> 01:08:38.210
Use your brain.

01:08:38.210 --> 01:08:39.510
Get in the game."

01:08:39.510 --> 01:08:40.810
And that's what it's all about.

01:08:40.810 --> 01:08:44.880
If you're a young person today,
you pick your party and start

01:08:44.880 --> 01:08:48.220
at the lowest level and bring
your influence and your brains

01:08:48.220 --> 01:08:53.560
to that party -- to the lowest
level, then the county, whatever.

01:08:53.560 --> 01:08:56.930
Instead of just, you know,
carrying a placard or bitching.

01:08:56.930 --> 01:08:58.230
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: Good advice.

01:08:58.230 --> 01:09:03.510
We have -- I think we have
two more quick questions.

01:09:03.510 --> 01:09:08.180
[ Applause ]

01:09:08.180 --> 01:09:11.040
&gt;&gt; John Van Oudenaren: I want to
throw one in real quickly back

01:09:11.040 --> 01:09:15.070
on security: Should
Guantanamo be shut down?

01:09:15.070 --> 01:09:17.710 position:56%
Is it more -- President Obama argues

01:09:17.710 --> 01:09:22.610
that it is inciting some terrorist
attacks against the United States.

01:09:22.610 --> 01:09:26.990
And why shouldn't some of those
detainees who are too dangerous

01:09:26.990 --> 01:09:29.920
to let them go back to wherever
they came from go into a kind

01:09:29.920 --> 01:09:32.630
of a super max American prison?

01:09:32.630 --> 01:09:36.150
&gt;&gt; Alan Simpson: Go ahead, Norm,
before I give them [inaudible].

01:09:36.150 --> 01:09:37.450
&gt;&gt; Norman Mineta: Yeah.

01:09:37.450 --> 01:09:44.190
I, in fact, was at Guantanamo
on Thanksgiving Day of 2002

01:09:44.190 --> 01:09:47.040
when they were just
starting to come in.

01:09:47.040 --> 01:09:54.130 position:56%
And I think there were five Al-Qaeda
prisoners there at the time.

01:09:54.130 --> 01:09:58.310
I think there was a great
deal of justification

01:09:58.310 --> 01:10:03.180
for establishing Guantanamo
at the time.

01:10:03.180 --> 01:10:08.720
And since then I think we have
other ways of dealing with it.

01:10:08.720 --> 01:10:15.170
And I don't think we need
Guantanamo as it is, as we know it.

01:10:15.170 --> 01:10:16.890
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: Do you
agree with that, Senator?

01:10:16.890 --> 01:10:18.190
&gt;&gt; Alan Simpson: How
many are there now?

01:10:18.190 --> 01:10:19.490
Eighty? Sixty?

01:10:19.490 --> 01:10:20.790
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: It's under ninety.

01:10:20.790 --> 01:10:23.350
&gt;&gt; Alan Simpson: But don't forget,
every one of them had a lawyer.

01:10:23.350 --> 01:10:26.080
They've all tried hard
and they failed.

01:10:26.080 --> 01:10:28.410
And at some point in time --

01:10:28.410 --> 01:10:29.720
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: And no other
country wants them, either.

01:10:29.720 --> 01:10:31.020
&gt;&gt; Alan Simpson: What?

01:10:31.020 --> 01:10:32.320
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: No other
country wants them, either.

01:10:32.320 --> 01:10:33.620
&gt;&gt; Alan Simpson: No.

01:10:33.620 --> 01:10:34.940
And any Congressman
that will say, "Well,

01:10:34.940 --> 01:10:38.800
bring them to my state,"
is not long in office.

01:10:38.800 --> 01:10:40.790
And they've already shown up.

01:10:40.790 --> 01:10:42.870
Don't bring them to New York.

01:10:42.870 --> 01:10:45.420
And the president is
obsessed by this.

01:10:45.420 --> 01:10:49.780
He made a promise and he wants
desperately to carry it out.

01:10:49.780 --> 01:10:53.800
But it's never going to
happen under his jurisdiction.

01:10:53.800 --> 01:10:56.700 position:56%
We sent five guys off the other day.

01:10:56.700 --> 01:10:59.950
Five went before and now they're
head of the Yemen operation

01:10:59.950 --> 01:11:01.940
down there blowing things up.

01:11:01.940 --> 01:11:04.190
So at some point in
time we say in the West,

01:11:04.190 --> 01:11:06.710
"If your horse drops dead,
it's best to get off."

01:11:06.710 --> 01:11:12.540
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: That's
Wyoming wisdom.

01:11:12.540 --> 01:11:15.160
Last question.

01:11:15.160 --> 01:11:23.200
I think we stumped our
questioner [inaudible].

01:11:23.200 --> 01:11:26.270
No, please, go right ahead.

01:11:26.270 --> 01:11:27.570
&gt;&gt; For our final question
from Hawaii again:

01:11:27.570 --> 01:11:29.700
Have your political
views ever gotten

01:11:29.700 --> 01:11:31.900
in the way of your friendship?

01:11:31.900 --> 01:11:35.260
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: Have your
political views ever gotten

01:11:35.260 --> 01:11:38.920
in the way of your friendship?

01:11:38.920 --> 01:11:40.920
&gt;&gt; Alan Simpson: Of our friendship?

01:11:40.920 --> 01:11:42.840
I love this guy.

01:11:42.840 --> 01:11:48.380
And we -- when he called me to
work on the reparations bill,

01:11:48.380 --> 01:11:50.230
it was very controversial.

01:11:50.230 --> 01:11:54.190
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: What year was this?

01:11:54.190 --> 01:11:55.490
&gt;&gt; Alan Simpson: This
was [inaudible]

01:11:55.490 --> 01:11:57.040 position:56%
but my colleague was Malcolm Wallop.

01:11:57.040 --> 01:11:58.880
There are people who
remember Malcolm;

01:11:58.880 --> 01:12:01.470
he was violently opposed to it.

01:12:01.470 --> 01:12:02.860
He said, "Who's next?

01:12:02.860 --> 01:12:04.710
We going to do something
with the blacks?

01:12:04.710 --> 01:12:06.080
How about the Native Americans?

01:12:06.080 --> 01:12:07.880
Who is next of the aggrieved?"

01:12:07.880 --> 01:12:14.390
And he was [inaudible] finally
said, "Look, I was there and I was

01:12:14.390 --> 01:12:18.800
in that camp and I know Norm
and what they're doing."

01:12:18.800 --> 01:12:21.360
Some people refused the money.

01:12:21.360 --> 01:12:24.220
They said, "It isn't about
money; I'm still embarrassed

01:12:24.220 --> 01:12:27.670
that they threw me in
this incarceration."

01:12:27.670 --> 01:12:34.730
So friendship is a beautiful thing.

01:12:34.730 --> 01:12:40.440
And we never -- I don't think
either of us ever since we were 12

01:12:40.440 --> 01:12:44.810
and now we're 84 have ever looked
at each other and say, "By God,

01:12:44.810 --> 01:12:48.970
I don't agree with you at all
on that issue of politics."

01:12:48.970 --> 01:12:53.250
And he served two presidents
-- a Democrat and a Republican.

01:12:53.250 --> 01:12:56.540
I loved it when Bush appointed
him and Norm said, "Look,

01:12:56.540 --> 01:13:00.210
if you're looking for a token
Japanese guy to go out and campaign

01:13:00.210 --> 01:13:04.110
for the Republican Party,
you've got the wrong guy."

01:13:04.110 --> 01:13:06.690
And Bush said, "I want you."

01:13:06.690 --> 01:13:11.580
And his loyalty to Bush and Bush's
toward him, you don't find that.

01:13:11.580 --> 01:13:15.460
You don't find people
who invite other people.

01:13:15.460 --> 01:13:18.400
Reagan made the White
House a social center.

01:13:18.400 --> 01:13:19.700
And Clinton was the same way.

01:13:19.700 --> 01:13:21.260
They loved people.

01:13:21.260 --> 01:13:22.560
But when you don't love people,

01:13:22.560 --> 01:13:24.610
never invite the other
guy over to your shop.

01:13:24.610 --> 01:13:26.290
You're paying a dear price.

01:13:26.290 --> 01:13:28.550
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: Secretary
Mineta, you get the last word

01:13:28.550 --> 01:13:33.100
on whether politics ever
affect that friendship.

01:13:33.100 --> 01:13:37.270
And on a broader scale, too, you've
lived and worked in Washington

01:13:37.270 --> 01:13:40.990
through Republican and Democratic
administrations, Republican

01:13:40.990 --> 01:13:44.940
and Democratic control of
the House and the Senate.

01:13:44.940 --> 01:13:47.250
&gt;&gt; Norman Mineta: Not really.

01:13:47.250 --> 01:13:52.500
I suppose the closest
I got to thinking

01:13:52.500 --> 01:13:56.880
that he had gotten off the
horse -- the wrong horse --

01:13:56.880 --> 01:14:02.590
was during the Justice
Thomas hearings.

01:14:02.590 --> 01:14:04.380
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: Clarence
Thomas hearings.

01:14:04.380 --> 01:14:08.300
&gt;&gt; Alan Simpson: He did
have a comment on that.

01:14:08.300 --> 01:14:14.750
Wasn't nasty, but I
voiced my opinion.

01:14:14.750 --> 01:14:17.510
And he told me to --

01:14:17.510 --> 01:14:23.080
[ Laughter ]

01:14:23.080 --> 01:14:25.640
&gt;&gt; Ann Compton: Gentlemen,
what a treat for all of us.

01:14:25.640 --> 01:14:42.340
Thank you, Senator Alan
Simpson, Secretary Norman Mineta,

01:14:42.340 --> 01:14:47.270
and for the kind of perspective you
have shared not only with friends

01:14:47.270 --> 01:14:50.750
and neighbors in Washington but the
kind of perspective you have shown

01:14:50.750 --> 01:14:52.610
to students who in Daniel Inouye's
institute are the positive forces

01:14:52.610 --> 01:14:53.910
that we all hope will be taking

01:14:53.910 --> 01:14:55.210
over when we get past 84,
all the way to 86 or 90.

